    ```javascript
function countGoodStrings(minLength, maxLength, oneGroup, zeroGroup) {
    const mod = 1000000007;
    const maxCount = Math.floor(maxLength / oneGroup) + Math.floor(maxLength / zeroGroup);

    let dp = new Array(maxCount + 1).fill(0);
    dp[0] = 1;

    for (let i = 1; i <= maxCount; i++) {
        dp[i] = (dp[i - 1] * (i % oneGroup === 0 || i % zeroGroup === 0 ? 1 : 0)) % mod;
    }

    let ans = 0;
    for (let i = 0; i <= maxCount; i++) {
        ans = (ans + dp[Math.floor(minLength / oneGroup) + Math.floor(minLength / zeroGroup) - i]
               - (Math.floor((minLength - 1) / oneGroup) + Math.floor((minLength - 1) / zeroGroup) - i < 0 ? 0
               : dp[Math.floor((minLength - 1) / oneGroup) + Math.floor((minLength - 1) / zeroGroup) - i])) % mod;
    }

    return ans;
}
```


    We first find the total number of digits that our maxLength will have.
After that, we use dynamic programming to count the number of ways to populate each group (1s and 0s).
We loop through from minLength to maxLength and then through the elements count of each group, and sum up the number of ways to arrange the groups in such a way that they form a valid binary string.
We accumulate that sum and return it as the answer.

